      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
One problem with Elon Musk=E2=80=99s offer to buy Twitter Inc. for about $4=
0 billion is that he does not have $40 billion. Of course he is very rich =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the richest person in the world, worth $260 billion by Bloom=
berg=E2=80=99s estimate =E2=80=94=C2=A0but most of that money is tied up in=
 the stock of Tesla Inc., SpaceX, the Boring Co., etc., and it is not obvio=
us that he would want to sell enough of those things to buy a new thing. No=
r is it obvious that anyone else would want to give him $40 billion to buy =
Twitter, given that he sees Twitter as =E2=80=9Cnot a way to make money=E2=
=80=9D and does not =E2=80=9Ccare about the economics at all.=E2=80=9DAnoth=
er problem with Musk=E2=80=99s offer to buy Twitter is that, if you ask him=
 where the money is coming from, he says things like =E2=80=9CI have suffic=
ient assets=E2=80=9D  and =E2=80=9CI am not sure that I will actually be ab=
le to acquire it,=E2=80=9D which do not inspire confidence that he has actu=
ally thought about raising the money.A third problem with Musk=E2=80=99s of=
fer to buy Twitter is that in 2018 he mused about taking Tesla Inc. private=
 for about $70 billion. =E2=80=9CFunding secured,=E2=80=9D he said, in an i=
nfamous tweet. It  turned out that he had had a single casual conversation=
=C2=A0with representatives of a Saudi sovereign wealth fund in which they d=
id not discuss the price of the deal or how much money the Saudis were will=
ing to invest; ultimately Musk  settled fraud charges with the Securities a=
nd Exchange Commission over this tweet. So the answer to the question =E2=
=80=9Cmight Elon Musk have made an offer to take a large public company pri=
vate, at a cost of tens of billions of dollars, without giving any real tho=
ught to where the money would come from?=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=9Cabsolutely ye=
s, and he=E2=80=99s done it before.=E2=80=9DAll of these problems mean that=
, if you are a Twitter shareholder and Musk says =E2=80=9CI am going to buy=
 Twitter for $54.20 per share,=E2=80=9D you might not believe him. =E2=80=
=9CShow me the money,=E2=80=9D you might reasonably say. And in fact, when =
Musk did publicly announce his bid, the stock price=C2=A0dropped, closing a=
t $45.08 on the day his bid became public. Musk=E2=80=99s proposal was cont=
ingent on =E2=80=9Ccompletion of anticipated financing,=E2=80=9D and that i=
s a big if.Similarly, if you are Twitter=E2=80=99s=C2=A0board, you might no=
t believe him. When Musk comes to you offering $54.20 per share, your first=
 reaction might be =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I think Twitter=E2=80=99s board=E2=80=
=99s was =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthat is not enough money.=E2=80=9D (Twitte=
r was trading in the $70s last summer, and the consensus seems to be that t=
he board would want a price at least in the $60s.)But your second reaction =
would probably be =E2=80=9Cwait, do you even have $54.20 per share?=E2=80=
=9D And if you asked Elon Musk that question directly, he would probably gi=
ve you an impish grin and say noncommittal things like =E2=80=9Cmaybe!=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwell I am very rich.=E2=80=9D This would be a frustratin=
g negotiating dynamic. You can=E2=80=99t negotiate a deal and then show up =
at closing and Elon Musk turns out his pockets and is like =E2=80=9Cwell I =
have like 69=C2=A0bucks plus some Dogecoin.=E2=80=9D You need to know if he=
 can get the money!The response by Twitter=E2=80=99s board to Musk=E2=80=99=
s offer was to put in place a poison pill to prevent Musk from buying too m=
uch more stock.  We discussed the mechanics and justification of the pill o=
n Monday. The basic mechanic is that if anyone (viz., Musk) buys more than =
15% of Twitter=E2=80=99s stock, that person=E2=80=99s stock goes poof, thou=
gh it is technically more complicated than that. The basic justification=C2=
=A0is that, if someone is going to acquire Twitter, the board would like it=
 to be at a high price, paid to all shareholders, in an organized process, =
and the pill allows the board to regulate the process.=C2=A0This leaves Mus=
k two main options. One is to negotiate with Twitter=E2=80=99s board and tr=
y to strike a friendly deal. This might be hard because the board probably =
wants more money than Musk is willing to pay, and also because there seem t=
o be strategic and personal disagreements between Musk and the board that m=
ight make friendly negotiations difficult. =E2=80=9CI am not playing the ba=
ck-and-forth game,=E2=80=9D Musk said in his initial proposal; =E2=80=9CI h=
ave moved straight to the end.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s an annoying way to s=
tart negotiations.His other option is to pressure the board into dropping t=
he pill, and the classic way to do that is with a tender offer plus a proxy=
 fight, as we  discussed yesterday:=09Musk can launch a tender offer to buy=
 all of Twitter's stock for $54.20 in cash. (Or, of course, some higher num=
ber.)=C2=A0The tender offer is a public, binding document filed with the SE=
C, open to all shareholders, and it will be  full of disclosures about his =
plans and, in particular, his financing. Shareholders will be able to read =
it and=C2=A0see if he has the money. If it looks like he does, then they wi=
ll be able to decide if $54.20 is a good enough price. If they think it=C2=
=A0is, they will be able to tender into his offer, submitting their shares =
for purchase. He won=E2=80=99t be able to buy them, though, because of the =
poison pill; the tender offer will be contingent on getting rid of the pill=
. But if like 90% of shareholders tender into his offer, then that is an im=
portant public-relations victory; he can go to the board and say =E2=80=9Cy=
our shareholders want this deal, let them take it.=E2=80=9D And then the bo=
ard might agree and get rid of the pill, and then the tender offer can clos=
e and he can buy the shares.=09Meanwhile, he can also try to get shareholde=
rs to=C2=A0vote=C2=A0their shares in a way that gets rid of the pill. Class=
ically, the way to do this is to run a proxy fight to kick out=C2=A0the exi=
sting directors and replace them with Musk=E2=80=99s chosen directors, who =
would get rid of the pill and let him close his deal. Musk can=E2=80=99t re=
ally do that here, because of Twitter=E2=80=99s corporate structure, but he=
 can run some sort of   informal symbolic proxy fight where he urges Twitte=
r=E2=80=99s shareholders to vote against the directors who are up for elect=
ion in May, or where he urges them to vote to declassify Twitter=E2=80=99s =
board so it=E2=80=99s easier to kick the directors out in the future. If 90=
% of=C2=A0shareholders vote with him for these things, that=E2=80=99s anoth=
er sign to the board that the shareholders want his deal and should be allo=
wed to take it.These things do not work automatically; even if 90% of share=
holders tendered into Musk=E2=80=99s offer and voted with him at the annual=
 meeting, the board could still tell him to buzz off. It could=C2=A0easily=
=C2=A0do that if it found another bidder willing to pay a higher price, but=
 it could also legally do that even without a higher bid; the law tends to =
defer to the board=E2=80=99s business judgment about whether or not to acce=
pt a merger offer. But most of the time directors care=C2=A0about what thei=
r shareholders think, and if all the shareholders want Musk=E2=80=99s $54.2=
0 then it=E2=80=99s embarrassing for the board not to give it to them.I gue=
ss Musk has a third option, which is to do nothing and tweet mean things ab=
out Twitter=E2=80=99s board. Honestly a totally respectable option; $40 bil=
lion is a lot of money,=C2=A0owning Twitter seems exhausting, and Musk does=
 have several other full-time jobs. A fourth option would be =E2=80=9Cbuy a=
 lot of stock, trigger the poison pill, and unleash absolute mayhem,=E2=80=
=9D which is not totally impossible given that it is Elon Musk.It does look=
 as if Musk is choosing Option 2. Last night he tweeted =E2=80=9C_______ is=
 the Night,=E2=80=9D which=C2=A0seems to be=C2=A0an annoying way to say=C2=
=A0that he=E2=80=99s considering a tender offer.=C2=A0The New=C2=A0York Pos=
t reported yesterday that he=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cis planning to launch the tender=
 offer for Twitter in 10 days or so.=E2=80=9D But to do that,=C2=A0he actua=
lly needs to find the money, and it is not clear how well that is going. Fr=
om the Post:Musk himself is willing to invest between $10 billion and $15 b=
illion of his own cash to take Twitter private, two sources close to the si=
tuation said. =E2=80=A6Nevertheless, it=E2=80=99s mainly outside financing =
that will carry the bid for Musk, who has tapped Morgan Stanley to raise an=
other $10 billion in debt against Twitter in the manner of a traditional le=
veraged buyout, the sources said. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Still, insiders say Musk a=
ppears to be having more trouble than expected in finding backers.According=
 to a source, Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter bid is drawing interest from investors=
 who have poured cash into his prior ventures, including Tesla and SpaceX. =
On the other hand, sources note that most private equity firms prefer to st=
ay away from political controversies and worry that they will not be able t=
o control Musk, according to a source briefed on the process.From the New Y=
ork Times:=C2=A0Morgan Stanley, the investment bank working with Mr. Musk o=
n the potential deal, has been calling banks and other potential investors =
to shore up financing for the offer, four people with knowledge of the situ=
ation said. Mr. Musk is first focused on raising debt and has not yet begun=
 to seek equity financing for his bid, one of the people said.=C2=A0=E2=80=
=A6Some investors are wary of getting involved in financing Mr. Musk=E2=80=
=99s Twitter bid, concerned about the risks of teaming up with the mercuria=
l billionaire and a company as politically contentious as Twitter, one pers=
on with knowledge of the situation said. For banks, offering a loan against=
 Tesla stock is also risky, given the stock=E2=80=99s volatility.And from t=
he Financial Times:Elon Musk=E2=80=99s $43bn bid to take Twitter private is=
 struggling to draw interest from several large institutions with the finan=
cial firepower to pull off such a large leveraged buyout in part due to con=
cerns over whether the social media group can become more profitable.Blacks=
tone Group, Vista Equity Partners and Brookfield Asset Management are among=
 some of the biggest private equity industry groups who have decided agains=
t providing an equity cheque for a buyout, people familiar with their think=
ing told the Financial Times.Musk or any other bidder wanting to take Twitt=
er private would need well over $20bn of new equity to complete the deal, w=
ith the remainder of the financing coming from debt or the participation of=
 existing investors who would swap their publicly traded stakes for an inte=
rest in the private company. =E2=80=A6The main concern for groups intereste=
d in financing a Musk-led deal is that Twitter does not generate enough cas=
h to service the massive amount of debt he would need to take on to the com=
pany=E2=80=99s balance sheet to complete a transaction.Additionally, many p=
otential lenders are concerned about Musk=E2=80=99s desire to promote great=
er freedom of expression on the platform, which risks hurting Twitter=E2=80=
=99s business by making it less attractive to advertisers, the company=E2=
=80=99s main source of revenue.One point I would make is that traditionally=
 these are conversations that you have=C2=A0before=C2=A0you buy 9% of a com=
pany=E2=80=99s stock and make a public offer to buy the whole thing at a pr=
ice of $54.20 (420 is a weed joke.[1]) I mean, you don=E2=80=99t need to sh=
ow up with signed commitment letters to have a first informal conversation =
with the chief executive officer about maybe doing an acquisition, but at t=
he point when you are making a=C2=A0public=C2=A0offer at a specific price, =
you will generally have at least=C2=A0talked=C2=A0to your bankers about whe=
ther you can afford that price. Musk seems to have been winging it when he =
made his initial offer, which is weird but also not surprising. And, althou=
gh he is in fact very rich, it=C2=A0does=C2=A0seem like he might be having =
a hard time coming up with the money, because $40 billion is a lot of money=
 for economically=C2=A0motivated investors to put up for a billionaire=E2=
=80=99s personal lark.Another point I would make is that Twitter=E2=80=99s =
board is doing a decent job of (1) asking these questions and (2) forcing M=
usk to answer them. In a sense, launching a tender offer is a way for Musk =
to put pressure on the board to do a deal. But in another sense, forcing Mu=
sk to launch a tender offer is a way for the board to=C2=A0pressure=C2=A0hi=
m to find financing, which is a prerequisite to a deal and not something he=
 would do on his own. In his own life, Musk is very casual about what count=
s as =E2=80=9Cfunding secured,=E2=80=9D as we know now from repeated experi=
ence. Writing a tender offer document will force him to be less casual.Broa=
dly speaking, what has happened so far is (1) Musk offered the board $54.20=
 per share to buy Twitter, (2) the board said =E2=80=9Cshow us the money,=
=E2=80=9D and (3) Musk is working on it. If he comes up with the money, the=
n the board will have to make some decisions, but right now the ball is in =
his court.Meanwhile in Florida,=C2=A0Ron DeSantis thinks this whole game lo=
oks fun and wants to get in on it:Florida Governor Ron DeSantis said the st=
ate could take action against Twitter Inc. for launching a poison pill defe=
nse to thwart an unsolicited bid by Elon Musk.=E2=80=9CWhy would you reject=
 the 20% premium?=E2=80=9D DeSantis said Tuesday at a press conference, acc=
using the company of censorship. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think that was a =
rejection based on financial concerns or business judgment. They rejected i=
t because they know they can=E2=80=99t control Elon Musk. They know that he=
 will not accept the narrative.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0DeSantis, a Republican and po=
tential presidential candidate, said he would be looking at ways to hold th=
e board =E2=80=9Caccountable for breaching their fiduciary duty.=E2=80=9DLo=
ok. One possibility here is that Musk will launch his tender offer, a major=
ity of shareholders will tender, the board will continue to say no, the poi=
son pill will remain in place, the tender won=E2=80=99t close, Musk will gi=
ve up and sell his Twitter shares, the stock will crash down to $30=C2=A0an=
d Twitter=E2=80=99s business will=C2=A0struggle. If that is the outcome,=C2=
=A0then a lot of people (Twitter shareholders, Elon Musk fans, Ron DeSantis=
) will be very mad, and not without justification. There will be lawsuits c=
laiming that Twitter=E2=80=99s board violated its fiduciary duties to share=
holders by declining a $54.20 offer for a $30 stock. And=C2=A0Ron DeSantis =
will absolutely kibbitz on those lawsuits, saying that Twitter=E2=80=99s wo=
ke board was so afraid of free speech that it robbed its shareholders of a =
good deal.  I think that Twitter=E2=80=99s board will win these lawsuits, b=
ecause Delaware corporate law does defer to the board=E2=80=99s business ju=
dgment in deciding to reject a merger and because the board=E2=80=99s use o=
f the poison pill seems clearly allowable under Delaware precedents.[2] But=
 it will be easy to sympathize with the lawsuits, because $54.20 is more th=
an $30.But none of that has happened yet, and I don=E2=80=99t think it is a=
 particularly likely outcome. I think=C2=A0the following scenarios are more=
 likely:=09Musk will never get his financing lined up, his cryptic=C2=A0ten=
der-offer tweets will never turn into a real offer, he never had the money =
to begin with, he was never going to do a deal and the whole thing was alwa=
ys vapor.=09Musk=C2=A0will=C2=A0launch a tender offer, but Twitter=E2=80=99=
s board and management will get their act together and make a compelling ca=
se to shareholders that their standalone business plan =E2=80=94=C2=A0which=
, one hopes, involves=C2=A0running Twitter like a business, as opposed to M=
usk=E2=80=99s plan =E2=80=9Cnot to make money=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0offer=
s more long-term shareholder value than Musk=E2=80=99s $54.20 today. So mos=
t shareholders won=E2=80=99t tender, the company will stay independent, Mus=
k will go away, the stock price will do okay and=C2=A0most=C2=A0shareholder=
s will be more or less satisfied with the outcome.=09The board will negotia=
te with Musk (before or after he launches his tender offer) and reach a fir=
m, fully financed deal at $54.20 per share or (more likely) a higher number=
.=09The board will find   some other buyer and reach a firm, fully financed=
 deal with that buyer at a higher price.And in each of those cases, in hind=
sight it will be clear that the poison pill was good and that the board=E2=
=80=99s efforts to slow Musk down were in the best interests of shareholder=
s. In Scenario 1, the poison pill flushed out the fact that Musk=E2=80=99s =
offer was vapor, before the board got too distracted engaging with him. In =
Scenario 2, the poison pill gave the board time to develop and communicate =
its strategic plan to create more value than $54.20. In Scenarios 3 and 4, =
the poison pill gave the board time and leverage to negotiate a better deal=
.=C2=A0Elon Musk is very impulsive, but that doesn=E2=80=99t mean Twitter's=
 board has to be. The board is doing its job here! Its job is to get the be=
st result for the company. That does not always mean doing whatever Elon Mu=
sk wants as soon as he wants it.
