=E2=80=9CGoldman Sachs Scraps Free Lunch, Marking End of Pandemic Office Pe=
rk,=E2=80=9D says  this Bloomberg headline. =E2=80=9CGoldman Sachs raises d=
aily dinner allowance by $5 after bankers complain,=E2=80=9D says this New =
York Post headline. Both true! From Bloomberg:The investment bank said Tues=
day that it=E2=80=99s transitioning back to =E2=80=9Cpaid-for-meal=E2=80=9D=
 service for breakfast and lunch on April 25, scrapping a pandemic perk. Go=
ldman also said it was boosting the stipend for meals =E2=80=9Cout of hours=
=E2=80=9D to $30 from $25, according to a memo obtained by Bloomberg.This i=
s a particularly clean case of maximizing what gets measured. From the Post=
:Litquidity, a closely watched blog for the financial set, had compiled com=
prehensive data on dinner allowances across Wall Street. It found Goldman b=
ankers were stuck in the $25 club alongside overworked peers at lower-tier =
and overseas banks including Citi, Deutsche Bank, Barclays, Credit Suisse a=
nd Jefferies.That=E2=80=99s at the chintzy end of Wall Street. By compariso=
n, Morgan Stanley provides $35 for meals, while at JPMorgan the rate is $30=
, the survey found.=E2=80=9CIn February, we called for David Solomon to inc=
rease the meal allowance for employees working late, as it was significantl=
y below other banks,=E2=80=9D Mark Moran, head of growth and operations at =
Litquidity, told The Post. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re happy to see that he has =
made the decision to increase his employee=E2=80=99s dinner allowance as GS=
 returns fully to the office.=E2=80=9DLitquidity put out a league table of =
dinner allowances, where a $35 allowance (Centerview, Morgan Stanley, etc.)=
 was good, $30 (Evercore, Greenhill, Lazard, JPMorgan, etc.) was fine, and =
$25 (Goldman, Jefferies, Deutsche Bank, Citi, etc.) was bad. Goldman was ba=
d, and there were headlines about Goldman=E2=80=99s cheap meal allowances a=
nd disgruntled bankers. Nobody did a league table of free breakfast and lun=
ch at investment banks, so Goldman got no points for being generous with br=
eakfast and lunch.[3] So Goldman sensibly added $5 to bankers=E2=80=99 dinn=
er allowance, saving the bankers $5 per day, and removed the free breakfast=
 and lunch, costing them considerably more than $5 per day. The result was =
a good Post headline and congratulations from Litquidity. The bankers are s=
trictly worse off, but Goldman looks better in the rankings, which is what =
it is optimizing for.Elsewhere in Goldman Sachs Group Inc. perks, David Sol=
omon is getting a cut of the deals now:The Goldman Sachs Group Inc. chief e=
xecutive and a tight circle of lieutenants are taking a cut of profits from=
 the firm=E2=80=99s private investment funds, according to people familiar =
with the plans. The perk could be worth hundreds of millions of dollars ove=
r the next several years to those executives, the people said, multiples of=
 their annual pay depending on how those funds do.The perk risks angering b=
oth shareholders and the Goldman fund managers out of whose pockets the mon=
ey will come. =E2=80=A6Unique among banks, Goldman is a big player in priva=
te investing. The firm has $426 billion of its own money and that of client=
s invested in corporate buyouts, loans, real estate and stakes in other inv=
estment funds. It is in the middle of another big fundraising push.In the p=
ast, the profits from those investments=E2=80=94known in the industry as ca=
rried interest=E2=80=94were split evenly between Goldman and the executives=
 actually managing the funds, a common enough setup that ensures everyone h=
as some skin in the game.Going forward those executives will receive just 3=
5%, the people said. Ten percent will be shared with Goldman=E2=80=99s roug=
hly 400 partners, part of a push to restore the prestige of a title that on=
ce guaranteed stratospheric wealth but has dimmed. Five percent will go int=
o a pool for Mr. Solomon and his closest deputies, the people said=E2=80=94=
fewer than a dozen people.This isn=E2=80=99t the first time Mr. Solomon has=
 gotten creative in efforts to juice his pay. Late last year he sought to s=
ecure a personal share of the profits from blank-check companies Goldman wa=
s planning to launch, according to people familiar with the matter. That at=
tempt, earlier reported by Bloomberg, delayed the vehicles=E2=80=99 launch =
long enough that the SPAC market fizzled. They haven=E2=80=99t gone forward=
.We  talked about the SPAC thing last year, and I suggested two explanation=
s for why Solomon would want to get paid this way. One is that taking upsid=
e on a bunch of different Goldman businesses is better than getting paid on=
 the success of the business as a whole: If one business does well and anot=
her does poorly, those things sort of cancel out as far as your performance=
-based CEO pay=C2=A0goes, but if you get carry on the business that does we=
ll, that isn=E2=80=99t canceled by the one that did poorly.The other, thoug=
h, is another case of maximizing what is measured, or here minimizing=C2=A0=
what is measured. In general if you are the CEO of a big bank=C2=A0you will=
 get paid an annual bonus with about eight digits, and journalists and anal=
ysts and shareholders will compare your bonus to the bonuses of other CEOs =
of other big banks, and if yours is egregiously high there will be complain=
ts. Whereas if you are allowed to co-invest on some deals and those deals m=
ake money, that is just a nice thing that happened in your personal account=
, not part of your compensation, and nobody will complain about it. Getting=
 a share of the private-investing (or SPAC) carry pool is compensation, but=
 maybe it=C2=A0looks=C2=A0different enough from your bonus that people won=
=E2=80=99t complain.
