stock. =E2=80=A6To lend credibility to his false story concerning Berkshire=
=E2=80=99s investments in IRB and increase the likelihood that it would be =
reported in the press, Passos fabricated a shareholder list that showed Ber=
kshire had made substantial purchases of IRB stock in February 2020 and was=
 the fourth largest shareholder of IRB as of February 18, 2020 (the =E2=80=
=9CFake Shareholder List=E2=80=9D). On February 22, 2020, Passos sent text =
messages with images of the Fake Shareholder List to the Communications Man=
ager, noting that a journalist could use the Fake Shareholder List to confi=
rm the purported news of Berkshire=E2=80=99s investment. Passos instructed =
the Communications Manager to share it with IRB=E2=80=99s public relations =
firm and ultimately with the press. IRB=E2=80=99s Communications Manager fo=
llowed Passos=E2=80=99s instructions and forwarded the information about Be=
rkshire=E2=80=99s supposed investment in IRB and the Fake Shareholder List =
to IRB=E2=80=99s public relations firm the same day. =E2=80=A6On February 2=
3, 2020, Passos also continued his efforts to get his false story concernin=
g Berkshire=E2=80=99s purported investment leaked to the press and reported=
 to the public. Passos sent numerous text messages to the Communications Ma=
nager suggesting specific journalists to contact, through the public relati=
ons firm, about publishing the story. Passos also texted his subordinate, I=
RB=E2=80=99s Director of Investor Relations, stating that they will plant, =
and Passos will spread, the story that Berkshire bought 28 million shares o=
f IRB. Passos further elaborated that he planned to use an old email with a=
 Berkshire executive to help build the story about Berkshire=E2=80=99s supp=
osed recent investment.Passos followed through on his plan to bolster his f=
alse story when, later on February 23, 2020, he sent IRB=E2=80=99s Communic=
ations Manager an image of an email he fabricated. The email, dated Februar=
y 21, 2020, purported to be from IRB=E2=80=99s CEO to a Berkshire executive=
, thanking Berkshire for its recent investment in IRB (the =E2=80=9CFake Be=
rkshire Email=E2=80=9D). The Communications Manager sent this additional su=
pposed evidence of Berkshire=E2=80=99s investment to IRB=E2=80=99s public r=
elations firm the next day. =E2=80=A6After the market closed on March 3, 20=
20, Berkshire issued a press release denying that it had ever invested, or =
had any intention of investing, in IRB.IRB=E2=80=99s Director of Investor R=
elations forwarded a copy of Berkshire=E2=80=99s public denial that night t=
o Passos, to which Passos responded with the Portuguese equivalent of: =E2=
=80=9CDamn=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re [expletive]!=E2=80=9DI do no=
t understand why he thought it would work? There is no accusation that, lik=
