      Algo stables
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about algorithmic stablecoins, in which a made-up cryp=
to token is used to maintain the value of another crypto token at exactly $=
1. In particular we talked about TerraUSD, whose price is maintained by tra=
ding with another cryptocurrency called Luna, and about how Terra is divers=
ifying its=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cforeign reserves,=E2=80=9D as it were, by buying B=
itcoin and other cryptocurrencies. The idea is that as Terra has gotten big=
, it can buy=C2=A0other cryptos to defend its peg to the dollar, instead of=
 relying on the value of Luna. I wrote: =E2=80=9CThe basic structure of the=
 trade is (1) Ponzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversification, (4) permanence.=
=E2=80=9DThis is a common=C2=A0way for algorithmic stablecoins to go, but t=
here are other possibilities. For instance you could have a  backed stablec=
oin (where each $1 stablecoin is backed by $1 in U.S. dollar bank accounts)=
, or an  overcollateralized stablecoin (where each $1 stablecoin is backed =
by, say,=C2=A0$2 worth of Bitcoin). And you could bop along doing that for =
a while, and everyone could be satisfied that it=E2=80=99s always worth a d=
ollar, and then you could=C2=A0transition=C2=A0it to being an algorithmic s=
tablecoin. Keep $1 on hand for every coin until everyone treats your coin a=
s being worth a dollar, and then start keeping $0.90 on hand, then $0.80, e=
tc., keeping enough money to defend the peg=C2=A0but not enough to=C2=A0ful=
ly redeem every coin in every scenario.This is more or less the strategy of=
 another algorithmic stablecoin called Frax, whose founder Sam Kazemian ema=
iled me yesterday:I can see why you didn=E2=80=99t include us as Frax goes =
against your entire narrative of (1) Ponzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversifica=
tion, (4) permanence since we start out at 100% collateralization and slowl=
y have gone down to ~85% so far. Our own structure is 1.) not-ponzi, 100% b=
acked normal bank 2.) acceptance, slowly unbacking 3.) permanence 4.) THEN =
finally ponzi like the Fed/USD. And go figure, FRAX has not lost its peg a =
single time.=C2=A0Honestly one of the best reader emails I=E2=80=99ve ever =
received.=C2=A0And, yes, I suppose a plausible history of traditional banki=
ng would go something like =E2=80=9Cfirst backed, then accepted, then Ponzi=
.=E2=80=9D[4]
