y=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0sub=
scribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bl=
oomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] Incidentally! I always write =E2=80=9C=
420 is a weed joke=E2=80=9D about Musk=E2=80=99s (and  also Twitter=E2=80=
=99s) love of the number 420, but when I do, people sometimes tell me that =
no, actually, Musk is referencing Douglas Adams=E2=80=99s notion that 42 is=
 the answer to the ultimate question of life, the universe and everything. =
This is wrong. For one thing, if Musk was desperate to include 42 in prices=
, he=E2=80=99d bid like $50.42, not $54.20. Also, Musk himself told the SEC=
, when it was investigating his $420 pretend bid for Tesla, that it was a w=
eed joke. From the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint: =E2=80=9CAccording to Musk, he =
calculated the $420 price per share based on a 20% premium over that day=E2=
=80=99s closing share price because he thought 20% was a =E2=80=98standard =
premium=E2=80=99 in going-private transactions. This calculation resulted i=
n a price of $419, and Musk stated that he rounded the price up to $420 bec=
ause he had recently learned about the number=E2=80=99s significance in mar=
ijuana culture and thought his girlfriend =E2=80=98would find it funny, whi=
ch admittedly is not a great reason to pick a price.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Anyw=
ay, happy 4/20![2] Just in case any Twitter directors are reading this, I s=
hould emphasize that this is not legal advice and it=E2=80=99s been a long =
time since I was an M&A lawyer. Right now I miss it though. What fun board =
meetings these must be! For the lawyers. Not so much for the directors.[3] =
This is sort of arbitrary and contingent. My understanding is that in Silic=
on Valley people really care about free lunches; that is a thing that tech =
companies use as a recruiting tool. On Wall Street, it historically is not,=
 and the Seamless dinner allowance is the key variable.=C2=A0[4] I don=E2=
=80=99t actually think that, and I don=E2=80=99t think Kazemian really mean=
s that. I think the history is =E2=80=9Cfirst backed=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0by gold, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthen unbacked and widely accepted.=
=E2=80=9D The  particularly *Ponzi* element of a lot of crypto stuff is the=
 idea of paying huge investment returns, in the form of tokens of the proje=
ct itself, to incentivize adoption. But now people mostly don=E2=80=99t tru=
st the dollar because you can earn 100% interest on dollars, or even becaus=
e you can earn a small amount of interest on dollars; they trust the dollar=
 because they trust the dollar, in a circular, widespread-social-adoption s=
ort of way. You don=E2=80=99t need to end up with a Ponzi scheme. But I can=
 see how someone might casually say something like =E2=80=9Cfractional rese=
rve banking is a Ponzi scheme, and that=E2=80=99s where we want to end up,=
=E2=80=9D and, sure, fine.
