ill seems clearly allowable under Delaware precedents.[2] But it will be ea=
sy to sympathize with the lawsuits, because $54.20 is more than $30.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But none of that has happened yet, and I don=E2=
=80=99t think it is a <em>particularly</em> likely outcome. I think=C2=A0th=
e following scenarios are more likely:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: dec=
imal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Musk will never get his financing lined up, his cryptic=C2=A0tender-of=
fer tweets will never turn into a real offer, he never had the money to beg=
in with, he was never going to do a deal and the whole thing was always vap=
or.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>l=
aunch a tender offer, but Twitter=E2=80=99s board and management will get t=
heir act together and make a compelling case to shareholders that their sta=
ndalone business plan =E2=80=94=C2=A0which, one hopes, involves=C2=A0<em>ru=
nning Twitter like a business</em>, as opposed to Musk=E2=80=99s plan =E2=
=80=9Cnot to make money=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0offers more long-term share=
holder value than Musk=E2=80=99s $54.20 today. So most shareholders won=E2=
=80=99t tender, the company will stay independent, Musk will go away, the s=
tock price will do okay and=C2=A0<em>most=C2=A0</em>shareholders will be mo=
re or less satisfied with the outcome.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">The board will negotiate with Musk (before or after he launches his te=
