ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">New York Post headline</a>. Both true! From Bloomber=
g:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The investment bank said Tue=
sday that it=E2=80=99s transitioning back to =E2=80=9Cpaid-for-meal=E2=80=
=9D service for breakfast and lunch on April 25, scrapping a pandemic perk.=
 Goldman also said it was boosting the stipend for meals =E2=80=9Cout of ho=
urs=E2=80=9D to $30 from $25, according to a memo obtained by Bloomberg.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a particularly clean cas=
e of maximizing what gets measured. From the Post:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Litquidity, a closely watched blog for the financial s=
et, had compiled comprehensive data on dinner allowances across Wall Street=
. It found Goldman bankers were stuck in the $25 club alongside overworked =
peers at lower-tier and overseas banks including Citi, Deutsche Bank, Barcl=
ays, Credit Suisse and Jefferies.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=
=80=99s at the chintzy end of Wall Street. By comparison, Morgan Stanley pr=
ovides $35 for meals, while at JPMorgan the rate is $30, the survey found.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn February, we called for David S=
olomon to increase the meal allowance for employees working late, as it was=
 significantly below other banks,=E2=80=9D Mark Moran, head of growth and o=
perations at Litquidity, told The Post. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re happy to see=
 that he has made the decision to increase his employee=E2=80=99s dinner al=
lowance as GS returns fully to the office.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Litquidity <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/27430244.257597/aHR0cHM6Ly9kb2NzZW5kLmNvbS92aWV3L2tpYWJ0cnBo=
cXY2aWhmcDc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb73f8ea5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">put out a league tab=
le</a> of dinner allowances, where a $35 allowance (Centerview, Morgan Stan=
ley, etc.) was good, $30 (Evercore, Greenhill, Lazard, JPMorgan, etc.) was =
fine, and $25 (Goldman, Jefferies, Deutsche Bank, Citi, etc.) was bad. Gold=
man was bad, and there were headlines about Goldman=E2=80=99s cheap meal al=
lowances and disgruntled bankers. Nobody did a league table of free breakfa=
st and lunch at investment banks, so Goldman got no points for being genero=
us with breakfast and lunch.[3] So Goldman sensibly added $5 to bankers=E2=
=80=99 dinner allowance, saving the bankers $5 per day, and removed the fre=
e breakfast and lunch, costing them considerably more than $5 per day. The =
result was a good Post headline and congratulations from Litquidity. The ba=
nkers are strictly worse off, but Goldman looks better in the rankings, whi=
ch is what it is optimizing for.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere =
in Goldman Sachs Group Inc. perks, David Solomon is <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27430244.257597/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvb=
S9hcnRpY2xlcy9nb2xkbWFucy1jZW8taXMtcGF5aW5nLWhpbXNlbGYtbGlrZS1hLXByaXZhdGUt=
ZXF1aXR5LWNoaWVmLTExNjUwMzkzMjYxP21vZD1tYXJrZXRzX2xlYWRfcG9zMQ/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBc3596823" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">getting a cut of the deals now</a>:</p><bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Goldman Sachs Group Inc. chief exec=
utive and a tight circle of lieutenants are taking a cut of profits from th=
e firm=E2=80=99s private investment funds, according to people familiar wit=
h the plans. The perk could be worth hundreds of millions of dollars over t=
he next several years to those executives, the people said, multiples of th=
eir annual pay depending on how those funds do.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The perk risks angering both shareholders and the Goldman fund manager=
s out of whose pockets the money will come. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Unique among banks, Goldman is a big player in private investing=
. The firm has $426 billion of its own money and that of clients invested i=
n corporate buyouts, loans, real estate and stakes in other investment fund=
s. It is in the middle of another big fundraising push.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">In the past, the profits from those investments=E2=80=94known =
in the industry as carried interest=E2=80=94were split evenly between Goldm=
an and the executives actually managing the funds, a common enough setup th=
at ensures everyone has some skin in the game.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Going forward those executives will receive just 35%, the people said. =
Ten percent will be shared with Goldman=E2=80=99s roughly 400 partners, par=
t of a push to restore the prestige of a title that once guaranteed stratos=
pheric wealth but has dimmed. Five percent will go into a pool for Mr. Solo=
mon and his closest deputies, the people said=E2=80=94fewer than a dozen pe=
ople.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This isn=E2=80=99t the first time Mr.=
 Solomon has gotten creative in efforts to juice his pay. Late last year he=
 sought to secure a personal share of the profits from blank-check companie=
s Goldman was planning to launch, according to people familiar with the mat=
ter. That attempt, earlier reported by Bloomberg, delayed the vehicles=E2=
=80=99 launch long enough that the SPAC market fizzled. They haven=E2=80=99=
t gone forward.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27430244.257597/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMDIvZ29sZG1hbi1leGVj=
dXRpdmVzLXdhbnQtdG8tZ2V0LXBhaWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQyMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21=
lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNDIwJnV0bV9jYW=
1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb64c7fdc" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked a=
bout the SPAC thing</a> last year, and I suggested two explanations for why=
 Solomon would want to get paid this way. One is that taking upside on a bu=
nch of different Goldman businesses is better than getting paid on the succ=
ess of the business as a whole: If one business does well and another does =
poorly, those things sort of cancel out as far as your performance-based CE=
O pay=C2=A0goes, but if you get carry on the business that does well, that =
isn=E2=80=99t canceled by the one that did poorly.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The other, though, is another case of maximizing what is measured, =
or here <em>minimizing=C2=A0</em>what is measured. In general if you are th=
e CEO of a big bank=C2=A0you will get paid an annual bonus with about eight=
 digits, and journalists and analysts and shareholders will compare your bo=
nus to the bonuses of other CEOs of other big banks, and if yours is egregi=
ously high there will be complaints. Whereas if you are allowed to co-inves=
t on some deals and those deals make money, that is just a nice thing that =
happened in your personal account, not part of your compensation, and nobod=
y will complain about it. Getting a share of the private-investing (or SPAC=
) carry pool is compensation, but maybe it=C2=A0<em>looks=C2=A0</em>differe=
nt enough from your bonus that people won=E2=80=99t complain.</p><table cla=
